                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d183">
                <head>183. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in Germany</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d183fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 762.0221/12–1156. Confidential. Drafted by Creel and cleared with
                            <persName corresp="#p_RJJ1">Reinstein</persName>. Repeated to Berlin,
                        London, Moscow, and Paris.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1956-12-11T13:07:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 11, 1956—1:07 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1607. At recent meeting in Department with General Hodes (CG <gloss
                        target="#t_USAREUR1">USAREUR</gloss>) latter expressed view recent Soviet
                    interferences with Berlin military trains and convoys were reflection of Soviet
                    nervousness over their own position East Germany. He surmised Soviet authorities
                    in Germany had probably received orders in general terms from higher up to take
                    special precautions for security of the area and that in course implementing
                    these orders at working level new checking procedures of past several weeks for
                    trains and convoys had resulted. He thought Soviets not prepared push matters to
                    point of major incident. He also considered it possible Soviet interferences
                    might have been designed initially to test extent to which tripartite solidarity
                    in Germany still existed after Suez crisis.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">
                            <persName corresp="#p_HHJ1">Hoover</persName>
                        </hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
